<h2>%%ReferenceStyle%%Book, editor as &#8216;author&#8217;</h2>
<hr>
<br>
<strong>REFERENCE LIST ENTRY</strong>
<br>
<br>
Add a reference list at the end of your essay citing all sources used in the body of your writing.
<br>
<br>
<strong>Format</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref">
	Editor, Initial(s) (ed.), Year of publication, <em>Title of book</em>, Publisher, 
	Place of publication.
</blockquote>
<br>
<strong>Examples</strong>
<br>
<blockquote class="ref">
	<span class="hover" title="Editor">Craven</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Initial(s)">I</span> (ed.)
	<span class="hover" title="Year of publication">2001</span>,
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of book">Australian cinema in the 1990s</span></em>,
	<span class="hover" title="Publisher">Frank Cass</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Place of publication">London</span>.
</blockquote>
<br>
Where there are more than two editors use the term (eds) instead of (ed.).
<br>
<blockquote class="ref">
	<span class="hover" title="Editor">Craven</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Initial(s)">I</span> &amp;
	<span class="hover" title="Editor">Smith</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Initial(s)">J</span> (eds) 
	<span class="hover" title="Year of publication">2001</span>,
	<em><span class="hover" title="Title of book">Australian cinema in the 1990s</span></em>,
	<span class="hover" title="Publisher">Frank Cass</span>,
	<span class="hover" title="Place of publication">London</span>.
</blockquote>
