<strong>IN&#45;TEXT CITATION</strong>
<br>
<br>
If there is no author, use the editor&#8217;s name.
<br>
The abbreviation for two or more editors = (eds)
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Craven (ed. 2001) discussed the successful&hellip;
	<br>
	or
	<br>
	The film starred actors&hellip; (ed. Craven 2001).
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
When the editor is referred to more than once in the same paragraph do not include the date in 
subsequent references, as long as the work cannot be confused with others cited. 
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Craven (ed. 2001) indicates that&hellip; Craven also illustrates that&hellip;
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>
If you directly quote fewer than 30 words, enclose the quotation using single quotation marks and
include the page number(s).
<br>
<blockquote class="in-text-citation">
	Craven (ed. 2001, p. 75) observes that &#8216;the ants had an advanced chemical defence system&#8217;.
	<br>
	Alternatively: In terms of sustainability, &#8216;the ants had an advanced chemical defence 
	system&#8217; (ed. Craven 2001, p. 75).
</blockquote>
<br>
If the quotation is greater than 30 words it should be displayed in a double&#45;spaced, indented block
(1.3cm) without quotation marks.
